Fig. 3 exhibits XRD patterns of the CuCo-Ni foam and CuCoCe-Ni foam. In the analysis of XRD diffraction peaks, the characteristic diffraction peaks at 44.2°, 51.5°, and 78.7° could be attributed to the metal Ni [44,45]. In the CuCoCe catalyst, the diffraction peaks at 35.5°, 38.7° and 48.7° can be attributed to the (11
1
¯
), (111), and (20
2
¯
) crystal planes of CuO (JCPDS 48–1548), respectively [46]. The diffraction peaks observed at approximately 36.5°, 42.4°, and 61.5° can be ascribed to the (111), (200), and (220) planes of CoO (JCPDS 43-1004), respectively [47]. Moreover, by comparing the XRD patterns of CuCoCe with CuCo, it can be found that the diffraction peak located at 28.5° can be indexed as the (111) crystal plane of CeO2 (PDF #43-1002) [48], which verifies the doping of Ce element. Fig. 4 a exhibits the morphology of CuCoCe characterized by transmission electron microscopy (TEM) and the corresponding high-resolution TEM image is shown in Fig. 4b. Lattice stripes with d-spacings of 0.18 nm and 0.25 nm can be found, attributed to the (20
2
¯
) and (11
1
¯
) planes of CuO, respectively. The lattice spacings of 0.15 and 0.21 nm were ascribed to the (220) and (200) crystal planes of CoO. At the same time, a uniform distribution of various elements on the surface can be confirmed from Fig. 3c–f, which is in agreement with the XRD analysis and can also verify the successful synthesis of the CuCoCe cathode.
